  "business_context": "Product records are the master catalog. They define what the organization can sell or quote — each line on a quote, opportunity, or order references a Product to identify what's being transacted. The Product-vs-Asset distinction is the cleanest split: Product is \"what we offer\" (catalog); Asset is \"what a customer has\" (instance). Pricing modeling varies: Salesforce uses Product2 (catalog) + PriceBookEntry (price-list-specific pricing) so the same product can have different prices in different price books. HubSpot uses Products with a single Price property. EspoCRM has Product with unitPrice; pricing variations require Price Books. Nonprofit deployments use Products less often — appearing for organizations that sell event tickets, publications, training services, or merchandise. When interviewing clients, surface \"Product\" by asking what they sell or charge for: a catalog of standard products/services with consistent SKUs, custom one-off services priced per engagement, or no products at all (donation-only nonprofits). The presence of a meaningful product catalog signals a non-trivial commerce or transactional motion in the CRM.",
  "catalog_id": "product",
